{
  "text": "The E. oleifera gSSRs detected 89 alleles, ranging from 1 to 13 across the Elaeis samples. Of them (alleles), 48.3% and 31.5% of alleles were specific to E. oleifera and E. guineensis, respectively, and 20.2% common in both species. Within the repeats, tri-nucleotides detected more alleles (mean = 7.8 alleles) than the other repeats. It would appear that the tri-nucleotide genomic SSRs show higher average PIC values than di-nucleotide repeats. This is most likely a reflection of the specific region of the genome targeted by the methylation filtration technique. Botstein et al. [CITATION_1] defined any locus (marker) with PIC > 0.5 as highly polymorphic. All the loci derived from the di-and tri-repeat gSSRs met this criterion, except sMo00055 and sMo00132. This shows that both the repeat types are generally informative in the samples analyzed. However, the mean PIC (0.402) from this study was slightly lower than that previously reported for E. guineensis-derived EST-SSRs (7, mean = 0.53; and 14, mean = 0.65) which were used mainly to analyze E. guineensis germplasm.",
  "citation_candidates": [
